<Article
  title="Maintaining Game Guides Over Time: Preventing Content Rot"
  description="Publishing a guide is easy. Keeping it trustworthy six months later is the real work. This is how we try to prevent our content from becoming dangerous over time."
  kicker="Content Maintenance"
  date="2026-06-25"
  heading="Maintaining Game Guides"
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="sec">
    <p>A lot of guides on the internet are effectively abandoned the day they’re published. Numbers change, mechanics get reworked, and players are still following the old instructions.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>How we try to keep things fresh</h2>
    <ul class="kv">
      <li><strong>Version tagging</strong>: Every critical data point is labeled with the patch it was verified against.</li>
      <li><strong>Feedback loop</strong>: Corrections sent to support@metaup.pro are treated as high priority. We aim to investigate within 48 hours.</li>
      <li><strong>Periodic audits</strong>: Every few weeks we randomly sample pages and re-verify data against current game state.</li>
      <li><strong>Change alerts</strong>: When major updates drop, we manually review all affected content.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>Why this matters more than you think</h2>
    <p>An outdated guide is worse than no guide. It gives players false confidence and leads to avoidable deaths.</p>
    <p>We would rather publish fewer pages that stay accurate than publish a lot of content that slowly becomes harmful.</p>
  </section>
</Article>
